<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
Heads up everyone, a forum moderator is needed to shut off some postings and poster. <p>
Head over to <a href=".forum.t-o-m-e.net/index.php">http://forum.t-o-m-e.net/index.php</a> and wonder about the postings from Pepotamo1985. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./PeterWiersig">PeterWiersig</a></strong> 
</p>
<hr size="3">
 <p>
feathin cleared the messages. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./FeathinSilyar">FeathinSilyar</a></strong>:  Yeah, it was some 21 total offending threads posted between two timeframes (that I got anyway, perhaps some other mods got others), but all I could do was delete the threads, as the user was an unregistered Guest.  He had a different IP (widely different) for every single post too. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: It was probably an automated attack. 
</p>
<hr>
 <p>
<strong><a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a></strong>: More unsavoury messages in the forums... Mods attention please! 
</p>

    <ul>

 <strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: I'll go look. Links would help, though, as well as whether it was on the forum or on the wiki. &lt;goes to look&gt; Where?? I'm not seeing anything unusual. 
        <ul>

  <strong><a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a></strong>: The forum, as I thought I'd mentioned. And they all seem to be gone now. And once again, 'twas Pepotamo1985...  
        </ul>    </ul>


<p>
<strong><a href="./FeathinSilyar">FeathinSilyar</a></strong>: Xandor cleared them out this time.  They are pretty easily apparent when he/she/it does it, as a post is made to nearly every forum, from "Help" to "Tolkien". 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Ah, okay. Thanks. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a class="nonexistent" href="./XandorTikroth">XandorTikroth</a></strong>: Yeah, I cleared them out this last time, but we need to do something.  I'm not sure what I can do, since a username ban is useless if he's unregistered.  Feathin, if he comes by again, we'll have to start banning by IP I guess... kinda sad, though... in all the years that the forum has been running, and as long as I've been on, I've never encountered a problem like this.   
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./HarryErwin">HarryErwin</a></strong>: These are known as wiki-spam and are posted automatically. I run a neuroscience wiki and was plagued by them until I forced posters to log in. What the perps are doing is mucking with Google's algorithm for determing the order in which web pages are presented. Yet another crew who I would like to give a barbed wire enema to. 
</p>
